{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17509345","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17509345"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:16:40+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:16:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11419"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11419","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11419"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.61,0.1,0.03,0.25,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4054"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52863"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4054","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4054"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11419"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38243"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"160"},{"type":"tags","id":"489"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4340"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4965"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"6610"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12800"},{"type":"tags","id":"12804"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4681"},{"type":"contributions","id":"4685"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11288"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14540"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15462"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42599"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43222"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44278"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52863","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/52863"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 29-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department of a small rural hospital with a four-hour history of sudden onset right-sided severe pleuritic chest pain and dyspnoea. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. Her last menstrual period was four months ago.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 104/min, blood pressure 135/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 19/min, SpO2 97% on room air, and temperature 37.4\u00b0C. Her BMI is 35 kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E. Cardiovascular examination reveals dual heart sounds with no murmurs or pericardial rub. Respiratory examination shows clear breath sounds with no crackles or wheeze. There is generalised swelling and tenderness of the right calf with pitting oedema up to the right knee. An ECG shows sinus tachycardia. A urine pregnancy test is positive.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Enoxaparin","Apixaban","Aspirin","Unfractionated heparin","Warfarin"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with clinical features highly suggestive of pulmonary embolism (PE) in the context of pregnancy, which is a significant risk factor for venous thromboembolism. The sudden onset of pleuritic chest pain, dyspnoea, sinus tachycardia, and signs of deep vein thrombosis (DVT) in the right leg are all consistent with this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEnoxaparin\u003C/strong\u003E, a low molecular weight heparin (LMWH), is the most appropriate management in this case. LMWHs are the first-line treatment for both antepartum and early postpartum DVT and PE as they do not cross the placenta. Enoxaparin is typically given as 1 mg/kg subcutaneously twice daily during pregnancy. It offers advantages of predictable pharmacokinetics, less frequent monitoring, and lower risks of heparin-induced thrombocytopenia and osteoporosis compared to unfractionated heparin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUnfractionated heparin\u003C/strong\u003E (UFH) is an alternative anticoagulant but is not the preferred choice in this scenario. While it can be used in pregnancy, current guidelines favour LMWH due to its greater bioavailability, longer anticoagulant effect, and lower rates of adverse foetal outcomes. UFH requires frequent monitoring of activated partial thromboplastin time (aPTT), which may be challenging in a small rural hospital setting. UFH is preferred in specific situations such as severe renal impairment, anticipated poor subcutaneous drug absorption, or massive life-threatening PE with haemodynamic instability.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWarfarin\u003C/strong\u003E is an oral anticoagulant that is contraindicated during pregnancy. It crosses the placenta and has been associated with significant foetal complications including developmental abnormalities, foetal bleeding, miscarriage, and stillbirth. It should be avoided in pregnant women and replaced with safer alternatives such as LMWH.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EApixaban\u003C/strong\u003E is a direct oral anticoagulant (DOAC) used for the treatment and prevention of venous thromboembolism. However, DOACs are not recommended during pregnancy due to the lack of safety data and potential risks to the foetus. They are known to cross the placenta, and their use in pregnancy is contraindicated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAspirin\u003C/strong\u003E is an antiplatelet agent rather than an anticoagulant. While it may be used in low doses for certain pregnancy-related conditions like pre-eclampsia prevention, it is not effective for the treatment of acute PE or DVT. Aspirin does not provide the level of anticoagulation required to treat or prevent progression of venous thromboembolism.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Low molecular weight heparin (enoxaparin) is the recommended anticoagulant for pulmonary embolism in pregnant patients.","Sinus tachycardia is the most common ECG finding in patients with pulmonary embolism.","Pregnancy is a significant risk factor for venous thromboembolism."],"references":["Gibson PS, Powrie R. Anticoagulants and pregnancy: when are they safe? Cleve Clin J Med. 2009;76(2):113-27. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/19188477/","Maughan BC, Marin M, Han J, Gibbins KJ, Brixey AG, Caughey AB, Kline JA, Jarman AF. Venous Thromboembolism During Pregnancy and the Postpartum Period: Risk Factors, Diagnostic Testing, and Treatment. Obstetric Gynecolical Survey. 2022 Jul;77(7):433-444. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/35792687/","South Australian Perinatal Practice Guideline [Internet]. Department for Health and Ageing.2004. Thromboprophylaxis and Thromboembolic Disease in Pregnancy. [updated 2018 May 14; cited 2024 March 02]. Available at: https://www.sahealth.sa.gov.au/wps/wcm/connect/a070e7804eedf080b699b76a7ac0d6e4/Thromboprophylaxis+and+Thromboembolic+Disease+in+Pregnancy_PPG_v4_1_14052018.pdf?MOD=AJPERES\u0026amp;CACHEID=ROOTWORKSPACE-a070e7804eedf080b699b76a7ac0d6e4-oqvcYj9"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38243"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11419"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38243","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/38243"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-11T09:44:23+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-11T09:46:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items